    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>Imagine telling your AI assistant on your morning commute via WhatsApp: <em>"Remind me to call the CA about GST filing at 4 PM."</em> Later, you sit at your desk, open the PersonalAI web app, and ask, <em>"What's on my plate for this afternoon?"</em> The AI instantly replies: <strong>"You have a reminder to call your CA about GST filing at 4 PM. Want me to draft the agenda for that call?"</strong></p>
    <p>This isn't magic; it's <strong>state synchronization</strong>. Most AI tools suffer from "channel amnesia" – they treat your WhatsApp, Android, and Web sessions as isolated silos. PersonalAI.cloud solves this by building a <strong>Unified Identity Graph</strong>. Every interaction, regardless of the entry point, is mapped to your persistent memory core. This means your AI doesn't just reply; it <em>remembers</em>, <em>connects</em>, and <em>acts</em> seamlessly across your entire digital life.</p>
  </section>

  <h2>The "Amnesia" Problem in Current AI Assistants</h2>
  <p>Most AI assistants today suffer from a critical flaw: they have no memory of your past interactions across different channels. When you switch from WhatsApp to Web, you have to start over. PersonalAI.cloud fixes this by building a persistent, unified identity graph that connects all your interactions.</p>

  <h2>How PersonalAI.cloud Synchronizes State</h2>
  <p>We don't just mirror chat logs. We synchronize <strong>state</strong>. When you interact with PersonalAI on any channel, the system extracts semantic intent, updates your personal knowledge graph, and pushes state updates to all connected devices in real-time.</p>

